It's easier to stick to initial judgments and say we prefer our gut feelings on people, situations, and objects. We => M

Parsing text takes too long; what you see on the fly is what you need to get by, in other words. Initial impressions can be a great thing in some scenarios, and it is probably how our ancestors millenia ago survived dangerous situations that required quick judgment in the moment. In today's society, it might be a lot less necessary. Consider how we judge a person on first meeting: are they well-dressed? Do they have a pleasant face to look at, their body built in a way that we consider good? On the other hand, this speaks nothing of who they are as a person; so what if they're sloppy looking? They could be the nicest person you'll meet all month. Most people would take this as an unpleasant sight though, and pass judgment instantly: "I don't think this person is good because they are messy."

Things like this bleed into every aspect of modern living. How many people stick to a brand because it has a certain look, and with that look others have an initial impression of who that person is? Consider the bigger names in phone and computer technology. What do you think of someone who is loyal to the Apple brand of products? How about people who prefer computers and buy purely from Alienware? These don't speak necessarily to who they are, or to the quality of the products, but it does speak to how we perceive both the people and the products they use.

Most of western society is very visual- and object-oriented. A lot of people take a 'what you see is what you get' approach to situations, other people, and things, instead of focusing on the nuances of each situation. We hear something about a celebrity after everyone has spent years loving them; it now colors how people react to that celebrity, like diehard fans insisting they couldn't do something bad because they look and act wonderfully.  => A

When we see someone new, we take our first visual impression of them as the one that colors all of our interactions going forward: are they put-together? Do they smile enough, have a pleasing demeanor? Most people stop there instead of digging deeper into the personality of acquaintances. We judge celebrities based on how they look, and not their actions.
